nt challenges to this myth. Through fieldwork at the Dominican-Haitian border, she gives a firsthand look at how Dominicans are resisting the official account of their national identity and instead embracing the African influence that has always been part of their cultural heritage.     Building on the work of theorists ranging from Edward Said to Édouard Glissant, this book expands our understanding of how national and racial imaginaries develop, why they persist, and how they might be subverted. As it confronts Hispaniola's dark legacies of slavery and colonial oppression, The Dominican Racial Imaginary also delivers an inspiring message on how multicultural communities might cooperate to disrupt the enduring power of white supremacy.     aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aAnti-racismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aAnti-racismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aBlacksxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aBlackszDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aCreolesxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aCreoleszDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aCultural pluralismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aEthnicityxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aEthnicityzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aNationalismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aNationalismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aRacismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aRacismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066330308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813584508423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813584508.jpg  a978-3-11-066330-3  RUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-066614-4  RUP eBook-Package 201